A True and Faithful
RELATION
Of the moſt
Remarkable DISASTERS
By the Late
Dreadful STORM
Which happend on the 27th Day of
November, 1703
Throughout England and Wales, both by
Sea and Land; the Perſons Names that
were Killd, or Hurt, or Damag'd :
With the Number of Ships, Men and
Guns; both Men of War, and Mer-
chant - Meti, loft or damaged on the
Sca-Coafts.
Alfo, a true Account of the great Dama
ges done in France by the Storm, (parti-
cularly at Paris) in Flanders, Holland;
and Spaint, &e. both by Sea and Land,
and the Number of People killed.
Collefted by an Ingenions Hand, to preſerve
the Memory of ſo Terrible a judgment.
Ljrenfed according to Deter.
London, Printed by 9. Bradford, in Weftmone
land-Court, in Barebelomes-cloſe, 1704.

A true and full Relation of the
most Remarkable Diſaſters
which happened by the late
dreadful Storm.
TN the firſt place we will recount all the
Accidents and Calamities done within the
City of London, the Suburbs, and the ad-
jacent Places; then enumerate the fatal Da-
mages we ſuffered in the Gountry and laſt of
all conclude with our Loſs of Ships, and Men
at Sea.
This fo violent a Storm blew from W. S. W.
which by its long Continuance, Duration, and
Force, gave occaſion to the Learned to con-
jecture that it was long gathering, and came
from a far. I will not preſume to compute the
Particulars of the Damage done by it, in and
about the City and Suburbs, both to publick
Edifices, and private Houſes, by the untiling
of Roofs, or blowing down of Chimnies.
Part of the Palace of St. James's was blown
down, and a Woman killd by the Fall of a
Chimney. Her Majeſty was alarmed, and go
up, with his Highneſs the Prince and all the
Maids of Honour, who eſcaped a liggal Dan-

The Garden Wall likewiſe of St. James's.
As Whitehall the Guard-Houſe was damaged,
and the Roof thrown downby which nine Sol
diers were much bruiſed, 3 of which dyed. Part
of the Apartment of the Archbiſhop of York, Lord
Almoner, was beat down, and a Footman killed

The Duke of Buckingham's Houfe fuffered ſome

were blown down, amongſt wliich the four

veral Trees in the Garden. The Lead of fe

It was obſerved that a Footman (noted for his
Agility of Body, and Swiftneſs of Motion )
being fent by a Noble-man, between two and
three of the Clock in the Morning, to en-
quire after the Health of his Relation, was not
able to make his way by the Water-ſide, the
Wind blowing fo fiercely from thence. Mr.
Midis an eminent Diſtiller in Piccadilly and
his Maid-Servant, were killed by the fall of a
Stack of Chimneys; at the ſame time his Wife
wes bruiſed. An extraordinary Inſtance of
God's Providence appeared in the Preſerva-
tion of a Family (7 in number ) in Golden-
Square, near St. James's, the Houſe being
thrown down on them all, they were all taken
out from under the Rubbiſh unhurt, to the
Wonder and Amazement of all preſent. A
Man was killed in Glaſhop-Straut, near the
aforeſaid Square. A Lady that lodged in Swf-
folk-Street, near the Pall-Mall, run into the
Street in her Shift, being frighted by the Fall
of the top of the Houſe, but the Chamber
Maid, who lay over her head, was buried in
the Ruins; who being afterwards taken out,
and Means uſed (by blooding, and other wife)
to fetch her to life, the lives to tell the Good-
nefs of God toward her in her Preſervation.
The Queen's-Bench Walks in the Temple, were
Wonderfully ſhattered ; particularly that Row
of Buildings next Wlaite-Eryars, were all un-
diled. The fine Rookery in the Inner Temple
Garden,
Garden, that had ftood near 300 Years, for
the moſt part is blown down. Lincolns-
and Grays-Inn have ſuffered in their Buildings,
ſeveral of their great Trees blown down. The
Dean of Paul's, and his Lady eſcaped Death
very narrowly; for they being terrifyed with
the Hurrican, got out of their beds, and went
down Stairs; they had not been there two Mi-
nutes, but they heard a ſtack of Chimnies fall
into the Room where theyhad repoſed all night.
Mr. Dyer, a Plaiſter, in Dean-Streci near Fet-
ter-Lene, being diſturbed by the Wind, and
getting up be endeavoured to ſtrike a Light,
and on a ſudden a Stack of Chimneys fell into
the Room, and ſtruck him Dead immediately :
His poor Wife, who ſtood near him, by the
kind Providence of God, only received a ſmall
Bruiſe on ner Legs. The Lead of St. Andrew
Holborn Church was rolled up in folds : Two
Boys of that Pariſh, belouging to Mr. Purefoy,
of Croſs-Street, near Hatton-Garden, lying
together in a Garret, were both unfortunately
killed by the fall of two Chimneys, and co-
vered by the Rubbiſh ; a third was taken up
much bruiſed and hurt, but yet living. An
Old-woman near ninety Years of Age, being
willing yet to live, had got out of her Cham-
ber, in fewen-Street, and was killed by a Fall
of a Brick-brake. A Woman and her Child,
living near Mr. Perer Skuages, a Diſtiller in
Pye-Corner, were killed by the fall of a Stack
